an do Sri Sri Chandi path *without initiation*. The rest of the confusion o=
n translation of mantras needs some clarification as there seems to be some=
 unnecessary confusion. A few pointers:<BR><BR>1. There are various sacred =
chants embedded within the Vedas, Puranas, Agamas etc. Broadly speaking suc=
h sacred chants can be categorised as mantras, stotras, kavachas, dhyanams =
etc. Some stotras too are also treated as mahamantras and mantras. The Samh=
ita portion of the Vedas too is referred to as mantras.<BR><BR>2. Undoubted=
ly mantras and stotras have to be chanted in the original. Reading a transl=
ation is not even comparable to chanting the original chant. So far it is f=
ine.<BR><BR>3. Whilst mantra, stotra and kavacha are all based on Sabda/Vak=
, tradition makes a distinction between
 them.<BR><BR>4. As per the traditi=
onal view one doesn't need to be initiated to chant a stotra or dhyanam. Th=
e case is not the same with most mantras. Mantras containing bijaksharas, a=
gamic mantras, mantras of Mahavidyas etc need initiation. This is the tradi=
tional view. Mantras from the Veda Samhita are not the same as these other =
mantras that need initiation, which are generally referred to as Agamic/Tan=
trik mantras. Whatever you call these mantras the actual idea is that these=
 mantras are integral parts of larger and distinct spiritual specialities t=
hat need initiation, as in the case of Mahavidyas such as Kali or Sri.<BR><=
BR>5. Vishnusahasranama, Sivasahasranama, Aditya hrdayam etc do not need in=
itiation as they fall under stotra category only. Lalitasahasranama and Dev=
i Mahatmyam are traditionally viewed not MERELY as stotras or parts of pura=
nas. They have a larger status as integral parts of a Mahavidya sadhana. Ch=
anting them without initiation is
 not recommended especially when the read=
er combines the navarna or shodashi mantras too as an integral part of the =
chanting.<BR><BR>6. I know from personal interaction that acharyas belongin=
g to both Kanchi as well as Sringeri paramparas recommend initiation for bo=
th the sadhanas of Sri Sri Chandi and Sri Vidya along with their respective=
 NAVAKSHARI AND SHODASAKSHARI mantras which are treated as an INTEGRAL LIMB=
 (ANGA) of the sadhana. Acharyas of both these traditions hold that one nee=
ds to be initiated to chant the Navarna as well as shodashakshari mantras.<=
BR><BR>7. Recapping my earlier stance, Devi Mahatmyam is a great text that =
has an independent status by itself as part of a Mahavidya. It is simultane=
ously a Mahavidya, a Yogasastra as well as an Advaitic text in the spirit o=
